"""
mkt-context: Psalms 80-85
Chapters: 80-85 (86 verses)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-psalms-80-85.py

Key context decisions:
- Psalm 80: Vine allegory (vv8-16); Rachel-tribe focus (Ephraim/Benjamin/Manasseh); threefold refrain escalating divine titles
- Psalm 81: Festival psalm (Gittith); divine oracle in first person from v5c; if-only divine lament (v13)
- Psalm 82: Divine council (edah El); three interpretive options; Jesus cites v6 in John 10:34-35
- Psalm 83: 10-nation coalition; Gideon/Deborah precedents; v18 most universalist verse in Asaph collection
- Psalm 84: Pilgrimage psalm; sparrow at altar; Valley of Baca; one day > thousand; YHWH as sun (unique in OT)
- Psalm 85: Post-exilic; tension of partial restoration; four covenant attributes meeting (v10) — chesed/emet/tzedek/shalom
"""
import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # INTENT: merge without overwriting any verse already present in existing
    # CHANGE? Do not alter the guard; concurrent agents depend on append-only behavior
    # VERIFY: run twice; second run should report identical byte count for psalms.json
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW_DATA = {"80": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 80: Asaph's Lament for the Northern Kingdom — 'Lilies of the Covenant.'</b> The superscription 'Shoshannim Edut' (Lilies of the Covenant/Testimony) designates a tune also used in Ps 60. The Asaph psalm addresses YHWH specifically as the 'Shepherd of Israel' leading Joseph 'like a flock' — the northern tribal vocabulary (Joseph = Ephraim/Manasseh) suggests this psalm originates in or addresses the northern kingdom, possibly in the context of the Assyrian conquest of 722 BC. 'Give ear, O Shepherd of Israel' — <i>ro'eh Yisrael</i> (Shepherd of Israel) — the royal shepherd metaphor applied to YHWH: the divine king as the one who leads the covenant flock.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'Before Ephraim and Benjamin and Manasseh, stir up your might and come to save us!'</b> — the three tribes named are the Rachel tribes: Benjamin (Jacob and Rachel's youngest), Ephraim and Manasseh (Jacob's grandsons through Joseph and Rachel's descendant). These were the northern and central tribes most directly affected by Assyrian pressure. The ark-procession context may be implied: these tribes marched behind the ark in the wilderness (Num 2:18-24). The prayer 'stir up your might' (<i>orerah et gevuratecha</i>) is a summons for YHWH to awaken his dormant military power.</p>", "3": "<p><b>'Restore us, O God; let your face shine, that we may be saved!'</b> — the first occurrence of the three-part refrain that structures the psalm (vv3, 7, 19), with the divine title escalating: <i>Elohim</i> (God, v3) → <i>Elohim Tzvaot</i> (God of hosts, v7) → <i>YHWH Elohim Tzvaot</i> (LORD God of hosts, v19). 'Let your face shine' (<i>haer panecha</i>) — the Aaronic blessing language (Num 6:25) repurposed as national rescue plea. The shining face is the antithesis of the hiding face that has allowed the national disaster.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'O LORD God of hosts, how long will you be angry with your people's prayers?'</b> — the lament question 'how long?' (<i>ad-matai</i>) is the standard lament form (Pss 6:3; 13:1-2; 35:17; 74:10; 79:5; 90:13). 'Angry with your people's prayers' — an extraordinary statement: YHWH is depicted as angry even at the prayers offered to him. The smoke metaphor (<i>aneshan</i>) in some readings: as smoke rises from an altar, so the prayers rise but YHWH responds with anger rather than grace. The prayer itself has become an occasion of divine displeasure.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'You have fed them with the bread of tears and given them tears to drink in full measure'</b> — 'bread of tears' (<i>lechem dimah</i>) and 'tears to drink in full measure' (<i>bashalishet</i>) — the covenant curse vocabulary: in the covenant blessings Israel would eat bread in plenty; in the curse, they eat grief. The measurement term (<i>shalish</i>, a third part or a large measure) indicates the quantity of grief is regulated — it is not random suffering but measured covenant discipline. Lam 3:15 similarly uses the 'bread of bitterness' image for the exile.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'You make us an object of contention for our neighbors, and our enemies laugh among themselves'</b> — the shame-dimension of the national disaster. 'Object of contention' (<i>madon</i>, strife) — Israel has become the source of mockery and dispute among neighboring nations. The enemies' laughter (<i>yilagu</i>) is the vindication of the enemy and the humiliation of YHWH's people: if YHWH cannot protect Israel, the nations conclude that YHWH himself has failed. The theological problem of national disaster is not only Israel's suffering but YHWH's reputation.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'Restore us, O God of hosts; let your face shine, that we may be saved!'</b> — second refrain, intensified to 'God of hosts' (<i>Elohim Tzvaot</i>). The divine title <i>Tzvaot</i> (hosts/armies) invokes YHWH's military capacity: the God of the heavenly armies is being petitioned by the earthly people who have lost their earthly battle. The refrain's repetition creates liturgical insistence: not satisfied by silence.</p>", "8": "<p><b>'You brought a vine out of Egypt; you drove out the nations and planted it'</b> — the vine allegory (vv8-16) is the theological heart of the psalm. Israel as YHWH's vine is a sustained metaphor in OT prophecy (Isa 5:1-7: the Song of the Vineyard; Jer 2:21; Ezek 15; 17; John 15). 'Brought out of Egypt' — the Exodus as the vine's transplanting: YHWH uprooted the vine from Egypt (slavery, Pharaoh's garden) and replanted it in Canaan. 'Drove out the nations' — the conquest as land-clearing for the vine.</p>", "9": "<p><b>'You cleared the ground for it; it took deep root and filled the land'</b> — the vineyard preparation: clearing (<i>pinnita</i>, clearing of rocks and underbrush), deep rooting (<i>sheresh</i>), and filling the land. The growth of Israel in Canaan under Joshua-to-Solomon is the vine's flourishing period. ANE vineyards required intensive preparation — the metaphor captures both divine labor and Israel's dependence on that labor.</p>", "10": "<p><b>'The mountains were covered with its shade, the mighty cedars with its branches'</b> — the vine's expansion at its height: covering the mountains and the cedars of Lebanon. This is the Davidic-Solomonic empire at its greatest extent: from the Sinai wilderness to the Euphrates (1 Kgs 4:21). The cedars of Lebanon (Baal's territory in ANE mythology — cf. Ps 29:5) are now shaded by Israel's vine — YHWH's people have overtaken even the domain of the rival gods.</p>", "11": "<p><b>'It sent out its branches to the sea, and its shoots to the River'</b> — 'the Sea' (<i>yam</i>) = the Mediterranean; 'the River' (<i>nahar</i>) = the Euphrates. The maximal extent of Davidic-Solomonic sovereignty. This is the fulfillment of the Abrahamic land promise (Gen 15:18: 'from the river of Egypt to the great river, the Euphrates') and the Mosaic promise (Deut 11:24). The vine has filled the promised territory.</p>", "12": "<p><b>'Why then have you broken down its walls, so that all who pass along the way pluck its fruit?'</b> — the reversal: the vine that YHWH planted and protected (vv8-11) has had its walls broken down. The vineyard wall (<i>geder</i>) was the essential protection of an ANE vineyard — without it, animals and passersby could freely plunder. YHWH as the one who broke down the wall is the most disturbing image: the divine vinedresser has become the destroyer of his own vineyard. The same image in Isa 5:5 (YHWH breaking down the vineyard wall as judgment).</p>", "13": "<p><b>'The boar from the forest ravages it, and all that move in the field feed on it'</b> — the wild boar (<i>chazir miyaar</i>) from the forest is the ANE symbol of destructive, unclean, violent plunder. The pig was ritually unclean for Israel (Lev 11:7); its ravaging of the vineyard is doubly defiling — the unclean animal destroying the sacred vine. The Assyrian army (or any subsequent oppressor) functions as the boar: brutal, unclean, unstoppable. 'All that move in the field feed on it' — general pillaging following the major devastation.</p>", "14": "<p><b>'Turn again, O God of hosts! Look down from heaven, and see; have regard for this vine'</b> — the pivot to petition: <i>shuv-na Elohim Tzvaot</i> (return, please, O God of hosts). The 'return' (<i>shuv</i>) is the repentance/return vocabulary applied to YHWH: just as Israel must return (<i>shuv</i>) to YHWH, YHWH is asked to return his attention to the vine. 'Look down from heaven' — the divine descent from the heavenly viewpoint to see the damage. The vine now identified explicitly: 'have regard for this vine' (<i>vephaqed gefen zot</i>) — the <i>paqad</i> (visitation/oversight) of YHWH invoked for restoration rather than judgment.</p>", "15": "<p><b>'...the stock that your right hand planted, and for the son whom you made strong for yourself'</b> — 'the son' (<i>ben</i>) — either the nation (Israel as YHWH's son: Exod 4:22; Hos 11:1) or the Davidic king (YHWH's son: Ps 2:7; 2 Sam 7:14). The ambiguity is productive: the vine-nation and its royal representative both claim the designation 'son.' YHWH's 'right hand' (<i>yamin</i>) — the planting hand (cf. v17: 'the man of your right hand').</p>", "16": "<p><b>'They have burned it with fire; they have cut it down; may they perish at the rebuke of your face!'</b> — the devastation described at its worst: fire and cutting down. ANE conquerors routinely destroyed vineyards and orchards as part of scorched-earth policy (Deut 20:19-20 restricts this for Israel's army). 'The rebuke of your face' (<i>gaar panecha</i>) — the same divine rebuke that drove the sea back (Ps 104:7; cf. Ps 76:6) invoked for the enemy's destruction.</p>", "17": "<p><b>'But let your hand be on the man of your right hand, the son of man whom you have made strong for yourself!'</b> — 'the man of your right hand' (<i>ish yeminecha</i>) and 'the son of man' (<i>ben adam</i>) — the Davidic king as YHWH's appointed human representative. The phrase is unique: 'man of your right hand' positions the king as standing at YHWH's right hand (cf. Ps 110:1). The 'son of man' designation, while here simply meaning 'human being,' feeds into the developing 'Son of Man' trajectory of Dan 7:13 and the NT.</p>", "18": "<p><b>'Then we shall not turn back from you; give us life, and we will call upon your name!'</b> — the covenant vow: if YHWH restores, Israel will not again turn away (<i>lo-nasog mimecha</i>). The vow of not turning back is the anti-apostasy pledge — a recognition that the disaster arose from Israel's turning away. 'Give us life' (<i>vechayyenu</i>) — the divine life-giving that makes covenant loyalty possible: life is the prerequisite for calling on the divine name.</p>", "19": "<p><b>'Restore us, O LORD God of hosts! Let your face shine, that we may be saved!'</b> — the third and fullest refrain: <i>YHWH Elohim Tzvaot</i> — the complete divine title. The escalation from <i>Elohim</i> (v3) to <i>Elohim Tzvaot</i> (v7) to <i>YHWH Elohim Tzvaot</i> (v19) culminates in the covenant name. The final plea is grounded in the covenant name: YHWH — the God who revealed himself as 'I AM WHO I AM' at the burning bush (Exod 3:14), who is the same God of the Exodus vine-transplanting — is asked to restore what his own name has promised.</p>"}, "81": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 81: Asaph's Festival Psalm — 'Gittith.'</b> 'Gittith' (<i>al hagittit</i>) is a musical term of uncertain origin: possibly connected to Gath (a Philistine lute), to the wine-press (<i>gat</i> = wine vat, suggesting an autumn harvest festival), or to a place or melody name. The psalm divides into two parts: a joyful call to festival worship (vv1-5b) and a divine oracle reviewing the covenant history and lamenting Israel's unfaithfulness (vv5c-16). The transition from human voice to divine voice (v5c: 'I heard a voice I had not known') is one of the most dramatic shifts in the Psalter. The psalm may have been used at the Festival of Tabernacles (Sukkot) or at the New Year (Rosh Hashanah), when the trumpet blast of v3 would have been liturgically fitting.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'Raise a song; sound the tambourine, the sweet lyre with the harp'</b> — the festival instrumentation: <i>toph</i> (tambourine/hand drum, associated with Miriam's celebration at the sea, Exod 15:20), <i>kinnor naim</i> (sweet/beautiful lyre), and <i>nevel</i> (harp). The plurality of instruments signals a full temple orchestra. 'Raise a song' (<i>seu zimrah</i>) — the imperative of festive praise: the community is summoned to collective musical performance.</p>", "3": "<p><b>'Blow the trumpet at the new moon, at the full moon, on our feast day'</b> — <i>tiqeu vachodesh shofar</i> (blow the ram's horn at the new moon). The <i>shofar</i> (ram's horn) was blown at new moons (Num 10:10) and at the Feast of Trumpets (Rosh Hashanah, the seventh month's new moon: Lev 23:24; Num 29:1). The 'full moon' (<i>bakeseh</i>, at the covering/full moon) may refer to Passover (first month, 15th day — full moon) or Tabernacles (seventh month, 15th day — also full moon). The dual reference could encompass both spring and fall festivals, or specifically Tabernacles (Sukkot) when the moon is full and the harvest complete.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'For it is a statute for Israel, a rule of the God of Jacob'</b> — <i>ki choq leYisrael hu mishpat le-Elohei Yaakov</i> — the festival is not voluntary but covenantally mandated: a <i>choq</i> (statute, the engraved/fixed law) and a <i>mishpat</i> (ordinance, the legal ruling). The festival calendar was a covenant obligation, not a cultural tradition. YHWH's claim over time — over the calendar — is an expression of his sovereignty over the whole of life.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'He made it a decree in Joseph when he went out over the land of Egypt. I heard a language I had not known'</b> — the transition verse. 'Over the land of Egypt' — the Passover statute was established when YHWH 'went out' over Egypt (Exod 12:12-13: 'I will pass through the land of Egypt that night'). Then: 'I heard a language I had not known' (<i>sephath lo-yadati eshma</i>) — the psalm's voice suddenly shifts: someone hears an unfamiliar language. Most commentators take this as the beginning of YHWH's divine oracle, where YHWH speaks in first person for the remainder of the psalm. The 'unfamiliar language' may be the divine speech itself — the experience of receiving the word of YHWH.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'I relieved your shoulder of the burden; your hands were freed from the basket'</b> — YHWH speaks in first person, recounting the Exodus. 'The burden on the shoulder' (<i>misevel shichmo</i>) and 'the basket' (<i>dudim</i>) — the specific labor of Egyptian slavery: carrying heavy loads on the shoulders and working clay in brick-making baskets. Exod 1:11-14 describes exactly this labor. The physical liberation from literal burden is the Exodus in miniature.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'In distress you called, and I delivered you; I answered you in the secret place of thunder; I tested you at the waters of Meribah'</b> — the divine first-person recital of the Exodus events: (1) the cry from Egypt (<i>ba-tzarah qarata</i>, you called in distress) and the divine response (Exod 3:7-9: YHWH heard the cry); (2) the divine response 'in the secret place of thunder' (<i>beseter raam</i>) — the Sinai theophany of Exod 19-20; (3) the testing at Meribah (Exod 17:1-7; Num 20:1-13) — the water-from-rock incident where Israel tested YHWH.</p>", "8": "<p><b>'Hear, O my people, while I admonish you! O Israel, if you would but listen to me!'</b> — the divine appeal (<i>shema ammi vaaodicha</i>, hear my people and I will warn/testify you) — the covenant lawsuit tone: YHWH as both the rescuing covenant partner and the plaintiff who demands a hearing. 'If you would listen' (<i>im-tishma li</i>) — the conditional formulation: the covenant blessings are contingent on listening. This is the Deuteronomic refrain: Deut 6:3-4; 11:13-14; the Shema itself is the listening command.</p>", "9": "<p><b>'There shall be no strange god among you; you shall not bow down to a foreign god'</b> — the First Commandment restated (Exod 20:3): 'no other gods before me.' 'Strange god' (<i>el zar</i>) and 'foreign god' (<i>el nekar</i>) — both terms for the rival deities of surrounding nations. The prohibition is covenantal: YHWH has an exclusive claim on Israel's allegiance. The covenant violation being diagnosed in the divine speech is precisely this idolatry.</p>", "10": "<p><b>'I am the LORD your God, who brought you up out of the land of Egypt. Open your mouth wide, and I will fill it'</b> — the Decalogue self-identification (Exod 20:2: 'I am the LORD your God who brought you out of the land of Egypt') followed by a remarkable promise: 'Open your mouth wide, and I will fill it' (<i>harkhev picha vaemale'ehu</i>). The open mouth as the posture of requesting: the covenant God offers unlimited provision to the one who asks with full expectancy. The metaphor may be from the feeding of young birds (Ps 147:9) or from the royal court where the king fills the open mouths of petitioners.</p>", "11": "<p><b>'But my people did not listen to my voice; Israel would not submit to me'</b> — the divine lament: <i>lo-shama ammi leqoli</i> (my people did not listen to my voice). The contrast with v8's appeal ('if you would listen') and v10's promise is stark: the invitation was refused. 'Would not submit' (<i>lo-ava</i>, Qal of <i>avah</i>, to be willing, to consent) — Israel refused to consent to YHWH's sovereignty. The ANE treaty violation: the vassal refuses the suzerain's terms.</p>", "12": "<p><b>'So I gave them over to their stubborn hearts, to follow their own counsels'</b> — <i>ashalcheihu bishrerut libbam</i> (I sent them away in the stubbornness of their heart). 'Gave them over' — the divine abandonment to consequence: YHWH does not destroy but withdraws, leaving Israel to the path it chose. Paul uses identical logic in Rom 1:24-28 (God 'gave them over'). The 'stubborn heart' (<i>sherirut lev</i>) — the Jeremiah vocabulary for Israel's unreformed heart (Jer 3:17; 7:24; 9:14; 11:8; 13:10; 18:12; 23:17).</p>", "13": "<p><b>'Oh, that my people would listen to me, that Israel would walk in my ways!'</b> — <i>lu ammi shomea li</i> (if only my people would listen to me) — the divine yearning in the 'if only' conditional (<i>lu</i>). This is the closest YHWH comes to lament: a mourning over unrealized possibility. The conditional shows that YHWH does not coerce: the doors of covenant blessing are open, contingent on Israel's listening. The divine grief over refused grace anticipates Isa 65:2 ('I held out my hands all day to a rebellious people') and Matt 23:37 ('How often I would have gathered your children...').</p>", "14": "<p><b>'I would soon subdue their enemies and turn my hand against their foes'</b> — the conditional promise: had Israel listened, YHWH would have defeated the enemies. The 'quickly' (<i>kimat</i>) of divine victory contrasts with the prolonged suffering of disobedience. The ease of divine military victory makes the current distress all the more tragic: the battles that Israel has fought and lost, YHWH would have won 'quickly.'</p>", "15": "<p><b>'Those who hate the LORD would cringe before him, and their fate would last forever'</b> — 'those who hate the LORD' (<i>mesane YHWH</i>) would become false flatterers (<i>yekhachashelu lo</i>, would dissemble/cringe before him) — the enemy's posture of enforced submission. 'Their fate would last forever' (<i>veyihu itam leolam</i>) — the submission would be permanent: no escaping the covenant victory of YHWH's people.</p>", "16": "<p><b>'But he would feed you with the finest of the wheat, and with honey from the rock I would satisfy you'</b> — the covenant abundance promised: 'finest wheat' (<i>chelev chittah</i>, the fat/best of wheat) and 'honey from the rock' (<i>dvash misela</i>). These are the Canaan-plenty images: the land flowing with milk and honey (Exod 3:8; Deut 8:8). 'Honey from the rock' appears in Deut 32:13 (Moses' song: 'he made him suck honey out of the rock') — the paradox of sweetness from hardness, abundance from the most barren source. The divine provision transcends even physical impossibility.</p>"}, "82": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 82: The Divine Council Psalm — the Most Theologically Significant Asaph Psalm.</b> Ps 82 is one of the most theologically charged and debated texts in the OT. It depicts YHWH presiding over the <i>adat El</i> (assembly/council of El/God) — the divine council of the ANE, which in Ugaritic texts is El's court of divine beings. The three main interpretations: (1) YHWH judging the pagan gods of the nations (the ANE polytheistic framework being absorbed and transcended); (2) YHWH judging corrupt human judges who have been called 'gods' by virtue of their divine-representative role (cf. Exod 21:6; 22:8-9, 28; John 10:34-35); (3) YHWH judging angelic beings entrusted with governance of the nations (Deut 32:8: 'according to the number of the sons of God'; cf. Dan 10). Jesus quotes v6 in John 10:34-35 in the context of the charge that claiming divine sonship is blasphemy.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'How long will you judge unjustly and show partiality to the wicked?'</b> — the divine indictment of the council members. Whether divine beings or human judges, the charge is the same: unjust judgment and partiality toward the wicked. In the ANE, the divine council was supposed to ensure cosmic justice; corrupt council-members meant a cosmos in moral disorder. The failure of justice in the created order is traced to corruption at the governing level.</p>", "3": "<p><b>'Give justice to the weak and the fatherless; maintain the right of the afflicted and the destitute'</b> — the divine council's mandate: to protect the vulnerable. In ancient Israel's legal system, the 'elders at the gate' were responsible for legal protection of the widow, orphan, and sojourner (Exod 22:22-24; Deut 10:18; 27:19). The divine council's members share this mandate at the cosmic level. Their failure to enforce it represents a catastrophic failure of the created moral order.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'Rescue the weak and the needy; deliver them from the hand of the wicked'</b> — the rescue mandate: not merely legal adjudication but active deliverance. The weak (<i>dal</i>), needy (<i>evyon</i>), and those in the hand of the wicked (<i>rasha</i>) are the triple-protected class of covenant law. YHWH's own self-description includes protection of these groups (Deut 10:17-18: 'the LORD your God... executes justice for the fatherless and the widow, and loves the sojourner'); the council-members are supposed to extend this protection throughout creation.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'They have neither knowledge nor understanding, they walk about in darkness; all the foundations of the earth are shaken'</b> — the diagnosis of the council's failure: <i>lo yadu velo yavinnu</i> (they do not know and they do not understand) — moral and intellectual blindness. 'Walk about in darkness' (<i>bachashechah yithallachu</i>) — the darkness of moral disorder. 'All the foundations of the earth are shaken' (<i>yimotu kol-mosdei aretz</i>) — the cosmic consequences of judicial corruption: when those who govern the creation fail, the physical creation itself becomes unstable. Moral disorder has cosmological effects.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'I said, You are gods, sons of the Most High, all of you'</b> — <i>ani amarti elohim atem uvene elyon kulchem</i> — the divine declaration of the council-members' status: they are <i>elohim</i> (gods/divine beings) and <i>bene elyon</i> (sons of the Most High). This was their appointed dignity. Jesus quotes this verse in John 10:34-35 to argue: if the OT calls those to whom the word of God came 'gods,' then claiming to be the Son of God is not blasphemy. The verse establishes a precedent for divine-representative status through divine appointment.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'Nevertheless, like men you shall die, and fall like any prince'</b> — the reversal of the dignity of v6: despite being called <i>elohim</i>, they will die <i>ke'adam</i> (like men/Adam). The mortality of the divine council members is the judgment for their moral failure. In the ANE, death was what distinguished mortals from the gods; here the gods are condemned to mortal death. 'Fall like any prince' (<i>kachad hasarim tipolu</i>) — their end is the same as the most powerful human ruler who has been deposed: they fall.</p>", "8": "<p><b>'Arise, O God, judge the earth; for you shall inherit all the nations!'</b> — the psalm closes with a prayer for YHWH to take direct sovereignty over all the nations, bypassing the corrupt council. 'Arise, O God' (<i>qumah Elohim</i>) — the divine arising to action. 'Judge the earth' (<i>shophta haaretz</i>) — YHWH himself exercising the justice that the council members failed to render. 'You shall inherit all the nations' (<i>ki attah tinchal bekhol hagoyim</i>) — the eschatological universalism: YHWH's inheritance is all peoples, not just Israel. This prayer forms the basis of the NT's universal mission and the eschatological judgment of all nations.</p>"}, "83": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 83: Asaph's Pan-National Enemy Lament — Ten Nations Conspiring Against Israel.</b> The final Asaph psalm (Pss 50, 73-83 form the Asaph collection). Ps 83 contains the longest enemy-list in the Psalter: ten nations or peoples conspiring to destroy Israel. The historical occasion is uncertain — some have connected it to Jehoshaphat's crisis (2 Chr 20: Moab, Ammon, and Meunites attacking), or to the post-exilic period, or to an eschatological scenario. The sheer breadth of the coalition (including Assyria, v8) suggests either a telescoping of multiple threats or a comprehensive future vision.</p><p><b>'O God, do not keep silence; do not hold your peace or be still, O God!'</b> — the urgent summons for divine speech: three synonyms of divine silence (<i>al-tachresh al-tishqot al-tishhot</i>) as the thing to be avoided. Divine silence = divine inaction. The enemies are active and vocal (vv2-8); the problem is YHWH's apparent silence in contrast.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'For behold, your enemies make an uproar; those who hate you have raised their heads'</b> — the enemies are both YHWH's enemies (<i>oyevecha</i>) and Israel's: the equation is a covenant claim. 'Raised their heads' (<i>naseu rosh</i>) — the posture of self-assertion and aggression: the lifted head is the opposite of the bowed head of submission (cf. Ps 3:3: YHWH who lifts the psalmist's head against those who have raised their own).</p>", "3": "<p><b>'They lay crafty plans against your people; they consult together against your treasured ones'</b> — 'crafty plans' (<i>ya'arimu sod</i>, they scheme with cunning) — political conspiracy, the war council. 'Your treasured ones' (<i>tzephunechah</i>) — those whom YHWH has hidden/treasured (<i>tzaphan</i>, to hide safely). The enemies target precisely what YHWH has chosen to protect.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'They say, Come, let us wipe them out as a nation; let the name of Israel be remembered no more!'</b> — the explicit goal of the coalition: national annihilation (<i>venachridem migoy</i>, we will cut them off from being a nation) and name-erasure (<i>velo yizakher shem Yisrael od</i>, let the name of Israel be remembered no more). This is genocide: not merely defeat but the elimination of corporate memory. The nations want what Pharaoh attempted (Exod 1:8-22) — the elimination of the covenant people as a people.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'For they conspire with one accord; against you they make a covenant'</b> — the nations form a counter-covenant (<i>berith</i>) against YHWH and Israel. The anti-covenant coalition: using the covenant-language to organize opposition to the covenant people. In ANE diplomacy, defensive and offensive alliances were ratified by treaty-covenant; the nations have formed such a treaty against YHWH's covenant people.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'The tents of Edom and the Ishmaelites, Moab and the Hagrites'</b> — the enemy list begins. Edom (southern neighbor, Esau's descendants), Ishmaelites (descendants of Ishmael, son of Abraham and Hagar; northern Arabia), Moab (eastern neighbor, Lot's descendants), Hagrites (an Arab tribe related to Hagar).</p>", "7": "<p><b>'Gebal and Ammon and Amalek, Philistia with the inhabitants of Tyre'</b> — continued: Gebal (Phoenician city/Byblos, or the Edomite Gebal), Ammon (eastern neighbor, Lot's descendants), Amalek (the perpetual enemy from Exod 17; Num 24:20), Philistia (the coastal enemy of the judges and early monarchy period), Tyre (the major Phoenician trading city, sometimes ally but often hostile).</p>", "8": "<p><b>'Assyria also has joined them; they are the strong arm of the children of Lot'</b> — Assyria (<i>Ashur</i>) as the military superpower backing the coalition: the 'strong arm' (<i>zeroa</i> = arm/strength) of the smaller nations. 'Children of Lot' — both Moab and Ammon were Lot's descendants (Gen 19:37-38). Assyrian backing of smaller states against Israel/Judah is historically attested in the 8th century (Tig-lath-pileser III's campaigns). The inclusion of Assyria gives the coalition both local and imperial dimensions.</p>", "9": "<p><b>'Do to them as you did to Midian, as to Sisera and Jabin at the river Kishon'</b> — the historical precedents invoked: (1) Midian — Gideon's victory over the Midianite coalition in Judg 7-8; (2) Sisera — Deborah and Barak's victory over Sisera (Judg 4-5); (3) Jabin — the Canaanite king who commanded Sisera. These are the Judges-period military victories where YHWH routed vastly superior forces through unexpected means. The prayer asks for the pattern to repeat.</p>", "10": "<p><b>'...who were destroyed at En-dor, who became dung for the ground'</b> — En-dor (near the Valley of Jezreel) was likely the site of one of the battles of Judg 4-5; Sisera's army was destroyed in this region. 'Became dung for the ground' (<i>hayu domen la-adamah</i>) — the most extreme form of ANE disgrace: unburied bodies decomposing into fertilizer. No burial = no honor, no rest, no ancestral memory. The enemies of YHWH become manure.</p>", "11": "<p><b>'Make their nobles like Oreb and Zeeb, all their princes like Zebah and Zalmunna'</b> — the Midianite leaders killed by Gideon: Oreb ('raven') and Zeeb ('wolf') were killed in Judg 7:25; Zebah ('sacrifice') and Zalmunna ('withdrawn shade/protection') were captured and killed by Gideon personally in Judg 8:5-21. These names were preserved as victory-trophies in Israel's memory. The prayer invokes specific named enemies as precedents for the current enemy leaders.</p>", "12": "<p><b>'...who said, Let us take possession for ourselves of the pastures of God'</b> — the enemies' goal stated in their own words: to seize <i>ne'ot Elohim</i> (the pastures/habitations of God) — the land of Canaan that YHWH claims as his own estate. The land is YHWH's pasture (Lev 25:23: 'the land is mine; you are strangers and sojourners with me'); the enemies want to seize it. The economic motivation of empire — taking the best agricultural land — is expressed in theological terms.</p>", "13": "<p><b>'O my God, make them like whirling dust, like chaff before the wind'</b> — two dispersion images: <i>galgal</i> (tumbleweed/whirling wheel) — the dry thistle or wheel of chaff spinning across the open field before the wind. 'Chaff before the wind' (<i>qash lifnei ruach</i>) — the harvesting metaphor: threshed grain has the chaff blown away. Both images express complete scattering: the coalition's unity dissolved and each member blown in a different direction.</p>", "14": "<p><b>'As fire consumes the forest, as the flame sets the mountains ablaze'</b> — the fire-imagery of total destruction: forest fire as YHWH's weapon. ANE rulers used fire as an instrument of conquest (burning cities, forests, crops); Ps 83 invokes divine fire against the enemy coalition. The mountain fire corresponds to the theophanic fire of Sinai and the eschatological fire of judgment.</p>", "15": "<p><b>'So may you pursue them with your tempest and terrify them with your hurricane!'</b> — the storm-theophany as weapon: <i>suphah</i> (tempest/whirlwind) and <i>searah</i> (stormy wind). These are the same storm-forces that YHWH directed at the Egyptians at the sea (Exod 14:21) and that Ps 29 attributes to the divine storm-lord. The prayer: let YHWH deploy his cosmic storm against the national coalition.</p>", "16": "<p><b>'Fill their faces with shame, that they may seek your name, O LORD'</b> — the purpose of judgment: shame (<i>boshet</i>) leading to seeking (<i>yevaqshu shimecha</i>, they may seek your name). The divine judgment is not merely punitive but pedagogical: the enemies' shame is intended to drive them toward seeking YHWH. This anticipates the universal conversion vision of Isa 19:22 (Egypt struck and then healed) and the NT mission to the Gentiles.</p>", "17": "<p><b>'Let them be put to shame and dismayed forever; let them perish in disgrace'</b> — the harder prayer: if shame does not produce seeking (v16), then permanent disgrace. The two-track petition (v16 seeks conversion; v17 seeks judgment) reflects the OT covenant pattern: blessing for the obedient, curse for the persistent rebel. The 'forever' (<i>leolam</i>) of v17 is the eschatological permanence of irreversible judgment.</p>", "18": "<p><b>'That they may know that you alone, whose name is the LORD, are the Most High over all the earth'</b> — the final theological statement of the psalm: the goal of all the judgment is knowledge. <i>Yeda'u ki attah levadechah shemechah YHWH elyon al-kol haaretz</i> (that they may know that you alone, your name is YHWH, are Most High over all the earth). The nations should come to know (the Exodus-knowledge formula: 'that they may know I am the LORD') through the judgment what they refused to know through revelation. This is the most universalist verse of the Asaph collection.</p>"}, "84": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 84: Sons of Korah Pilgrim Psalm — One of the Psalter's Most Beloved Poems.</b> Ps 84 is a pilgrimage psalm expressing longing for the Jerusalem temple and the joy of presence in YHWH's courts. The Sons of Korah guild (associated with the temple gatekeeping and music ministry: 1 Chr 9:19; 26:1-19) composed an ardent love-poem for the sanctuary they served. 'How lovely is your dwelling place, O LORD of hosts!' — <i>ma yedidot mishkenotechah YHWH Tzvaot</i> — the exclamatory <i>ma</i> (how!/how much!) expresses overwhelming aesthetic and spiritual delight. <i>Mishkenotechah</i> (your dwelling places, plural) — possibly the tabernacle precincts in their multiple areas, or the emphatic plural of the sanctuary's rich dimensions.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'My soul longs, yes, faints for the courts of the LORD; my heart and flesh sing for joy to the living God'</b> — <i>nichsephah vegam kalethah naphshi</i> (my soul longs, even faints with longing) — the vocabulary of intense desire: <i>nichsephah</i> (Niphal of <i>kasaph</i>, to long/yearn with physical ache) + <i>kalethah</i> (<i>kalah</i>, to be consumed, exhausted by longing, cf. Ps 119:81). Both soul (<i>naphesh</i>) and flesh (<i>basar</i>) sing — the whole person, interior and exterior, is engaged. 'The living God' (<i>El chai</i>) — not a static deity of idol-cult but the dynamically active God.</p>", "3": "<p><b>'Even the sparrow finds a home, and the swallow a nest for herself, where she may lay her young, at your altars, O LORD of hosts, my King and my God'</b> — one of the most charming images in the Psalter: birds nesting at the temple altars have what the pilgrim desperately longs for — permanent, unimpeded access to YHWH's presence. The sparrow (<i>tzippor</i>) and swallow (<i>deror</i>) build nests near the bronze altars of the temple courts. The birds are not conscious worshipers, but their habitual presence near the divine dwelling is the pilgrim's envy. 'My King and my God' (<i>malki v-Elohai</i>) — the personal covenant appropriation at the psalm's center.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'Blessed are those who dwell in your house, ever singing your praise!'</b> — <i>ashre yoshve veitechah</i> — the first of three beatitudes in the psalm (vv4, 5, 12). 'Those who dwell in your house' — the Levites and priests who had permanent access to the temple precincts. The pilgrim who visits occasionally envies those who can 'ever' (<i>od</i>, continually) be in the presence of YHWH. The temple servants have what the pilgrim travels far to experience briefly.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'Blessed are those whose strength is in you, in whose heart are the highways to Zion'</b> — the second beatitude: the blessed person has both their strength (<i>oz</i>) in YHWH and the pilgrim roads (<i>mesillot</i>) in their heart. 'Highways to Zion' (<i>mesillot bilvavam</i>) — the actual pilgrimage roads to Jerusalem are internalized in the pilgrim's heart: the longing to make the journey, the mental rehearsal of the route. The roads that lead to Zion run through the heart before they run through the landscape.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'As they go through the Valley of Baca, they make it a spring; the early rain also covers it with pools'</b> — the 'Valley of Baca' (<i>emek habaka</i>) — the word <i>baka</i> means 'weeping' or may be the name of a specific dry valley on the pilgrimage route to Jerusalem. In either reading, the transformation is miraculous: a valley of weeping or dryness becomes a spring (<i>maayan</i>) through the pilgrims' passage. Their tears become water; their longing transforms the landscape. 'The early rain covers it with pools' — the autumn rains that begin the new year make even the dry valley overflow. The pilgrimage journey transforms both the traveler and the terrain.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'They go from strength to strength; each one appears before God in Zion'</b> — <i>yelkhu mechayil el-chayil</i> (they go from strength to strength) — a unique phrase: the pilgrimage journey does not exhaust but strengthens. Each stage of the journey produces more capacity for the next. 'Each one appears before God in Zion' (<i>yera'e el-Elohim betziyon</i>) — the covenant obligation of the three pilgrimage festivals was 'to appear before the LORD' (Deut 16:16; Exod 23:17). The appearing (<i>yera'eh</i>) is the formal covenant audience with the divine king at his palace.</p>", "8": "<p><b>'O LORD God of hosts, hear my prayer; give ear, O God of Jacob!'</b> — the interlude petition: the pilgrim at the temple prays for YHWH's attention. The two divine titles: <i>YHWH Elohim Tzvaot</i> (LORD God of hosts — the most complete title) and <i>Elohei Yaakov</i> (God of Jacob — the covenant-patriarch title). The combination: cosmic power (<i>Tzvaot</i>) and covenant faithfulness (<i>Yaakov</i>) are both invoked.</p>", "9": "<p><b>'Behold our shield, O God; look on the face of your anointed!'</b> — <i>maginenu</i> (our shield) — YHWH as the covenant shield (Gen 15:1: 'I am your shield'). 'Your anointed' (<i>meshichechah</i>) — the Davidic king. The pilgrim's prayer for the king: YHWH's attention to the king's face (<i>panim</i>) is a request for divine favor. The pilgrimage psalm includes prayer for the royal patron through whom YHWH's blessings flow to the people.</p>", "10": "<p><b>'For a day in your courts is better than a thousand elsewhere. I would rather be a doorkeeper in the house of my God than dwell in the tents of wickedness'</b> — the famous comparison: one day (<i>yom echad</i>) in YHWH's courts > 1000 days (<i>alaphim</i>) anywhere else. 'Doorkeeper in the house of my God' (<i>histopheph beveyt Elohai</i>) — <i>histopheph</i> (to stand at the threshold/doorway, to hover at the entrance) — the most peripheral possible position inside the temple boundary is preferable to the most comfortable position in 'the tents of wickedness' (<i>ahale resha</i>). The contrast: covenant poverty at the temple edge vs. covenant-free prosperity.</p>", "11": "<p><b>'For the LORD God is a sun and shield; the LORD bestows favor and honor. No good thing does he withhold from those who walk uprightly'</b> — 'the LORD is a sun' (<i>ki shemesh umagen YHWH Elohim</i>) — uniquely in the OT, YHWH is called a <i>shemesh</i> (sun). Solar imagery was intensely politically charged in the ANE: sun-gods (Ra, Shamash, the Aten) were the supreme deities of Egypt and Mesopotamia. Israel's anti-solar-cult polemic (Deut 17:3; Ezek 8:16) made comparing YHWH to the sun rare. Here the comparison works: as the sun gives light and warmth to all creation, YHWH gives favor (<i>chen</i>) and honor (<i>kavod</i>) to those who walk uprightly.</p>", "12": "<p><b>'O LORD of hosts, blessed is the one who trusts in you!'</b> — the third beatitude closes the psalm: <i>ashre adam boteach bach</i> (blessed is the person who trusts in you). The pilgrimage psalm that opened with 'how lovely' and moved through longing, transformation, prayer, and comparison closes with the simplest possible covenant affirmation: the person who trusts YHWH is blessed. <i>Batach</i> (trust) is the covenant posture that organizes all the other elements of the psalm.</p>"}, "85": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 85: Sons of Korah's Restoration Psalm — Post-Exilic Yearning.</b> The opening verses (vv1-3) describe a past restoration in the perfect tense ('you showed favor,' 'you restored,' 'you forgave'), which most interpreters understand as the return from Babylonian exile (538 BC, under Cyrus's decree). Verses 4-7 then petition for a further restoration, suggesting the post-exilic community has returned but not fully experienced the promised renewal. The tension between 'you have restored' and 'restore us again' reflects the partially-realized eschatology of the post-exilic period: the return happened, but the full restoration described by Isaiah has not yet come.</p><p><b>'LORD, you were favorable to your land; you restored the fortunes of Jacob'</b> — <i>shavta shevit Yaakov</i> (you turned the captivity/fortunes of Jacob) — the exile-return formula used in Jer 29:14; 30:3, 18; Ezek 39:25; Amos 9:14. The specificity 'your land' (<i>artzecha</i>) and 'Jacob' (<i>Yaakov</i>) — the covenant-patriarchal name — ground the restoration in the particular covenant relationship.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'You forgave the iniquity of your people; you covered all their sin'</b> — the forgiveness accompanying restoration: <i>nasa avon amecha</i> (you bore/lifted the iniquity of your people) and <i>kissita kol-chattatam</i> (you covered all their sin). The two forgiveness terms echo Ps 32:1-2: lifting the iniquity and covering the sin. The exile was understood as punishment for covenant sin (2 Chr 36:15-21); the restoration from exile was therefore an act of forgiveness, not merely geopolitical maneuvering.</p>", "3": "<p><b>'You withdrew all your wrath; you turned from your hot anger'</b> — <i>asaphta kol-evratchah</i> (you gathered in all your wrath) — the divine anger withdrawn and stored away. 'Turned from your hot anger' (<i>shavta mecharon appechah</i>) — the divine repentance/turning parallel to the human repentance required for restoration. In the covenantal pattern, Israel's repentance produces divine 'turning' from judgment (Jonah 3:9-10; Joel 2:13-14).</p>", "4": "<p><b>'Restore us again, O God of our salvation, and put away your indignation toward us!'</b> — the pivot to petition: despite the past restoration (vv1-3), the present situation still requires <i>shuvenu</i> (restore us, turn us, Qal imperative of <i>shuv</i>). The double meaning of <i>shuv</i> is crucial: restore us (bring us back from a difficult situation) and turn us (turn our hearts toward you). The same word applies to divine turning (v3: 'you turned from your anger') and human turning. Restoration and repentance are both expressed by <i>shuv</i>.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'Will you be angry with us forever? Will you prolong your anger to all generations?'</b> — the lament question (cf. Pss 79:5; 80:4) about the duration of divine anger. The post-exilic community's experience: the temple is rebuilt (under Zerubbabel/Haggai/Zechariah), but the full Isaianic restoration has not materialized. The Davidic throne is not restored; the nations have not flocked to Zion; the material poverty of the return is far from the abundance promised. 'Forever' and 'all generations' probe whether this partial restoration is all YHWH intends.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'Will you not revive us again, that your people may rejoice in you?'</b> — <i>halo attah tashuv techayyenu</i> (will you not again revive us) — the reviving (<i>chayah</i> in the Piel/Hiphil = give life, revive) is what the partial restoration requires: more than physical return but spiritual renewal. 'That your people may rejoice in you' (<i>veyismach amecha bak</i>) — joy is the test of true restoration: the returned community praying for the joy that proves the restoration is complete.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'Show us your steadfast love, O LORD, and grant us your salvation'</b> — the covenant petition: <i>chesed</i> (steadfast/covenant love) and <i>yeshuah</i> (salvation) — the twin pillars of the covenant promise. The 'showing' (<i>areenu</i>, show us, make visible) of <i>chesed</i> is the request that the invisible covenant love become experientially visible in the community's life. The salvation (<i>yeshuah</i>) is the <i>yeshu'at YHWH</i> (salvation of YHWH) that Israel's whole history has anticipated.</p>", "8": "<p><b>'Let me hear what God the LORD will speak, for he will speak peace to his people, to his saints; but let them not turn back to folly'</b> — the liturgical listening posture: the psalmist waits for the divine oracle. 'He will speak peace' (<i>yedabber shalom</i>) — the anticipated content of the divine word is <i>shalom</i> (wholeness/peace). This suggests a liturgical setting where a priest or prophet delivered an assurance-oracle (<i>Heilsorakel</i>) after the lament was offered. 'Let them not turn back to folly' (<i>al-yashuvou lekesilah</i>) — the warning embedded in the hope: divine peace cannot be claimed while returning to the covenant-foolishness that caused the exile.</p>", "9": "<p><b>'Surely his salvation is near to those who fear him, that glory may dwell in our land'</b> — the divine oracle received: salvation is <i>qarov</i> (near) for the fearers. 'That glory may dwell in our land' (<i>lishkon kavod be-artzenu</i>) — the anticipated Shekinah: the <i>kavod</i> (glory, divine radiant presence) that departed from the temple in Ezekiel's vision (Ezek 10:18; 11:23) will return and dwell (<i>shakhan</i>) in the land again. Ezek 43:1-5 describes the return of the <i>kavod</i>; Ps 85 prays for it.</p>", "10": "<p><b>'Steadfast love and faithfulness meet; righteousness and peace kiss each other'</b> — the most celebrated verse of the psalm, one of the most beautiful in the Psalter. Four covenant attributes personified: <i>chesed</i> (steadfast love) and <i>emet</i> (faithfulness/truth) meet (<i>niphgashu</i>); <i>tzedek</i> (righteousness) and <i>shalom</i> (peace) kiss (<i>nashaquu</i>). In the present age these attributes are in tension: the demands of righteousness and the gift of peace; the expectations of faithfulness and the need for love. The psalmist envisions a future moment when they converge. Medieval Christian commentators saw this as a prophecy of the incarnation: God's justice and mercy reconciled in Christ. The verse has served in Christian preaching as a summary of the atonement.</p>", "11": "<p><b>'Faithfulness springs up from the earth, and righteousness looks down from the sky'</b> — the cosmic dimensions of the restoration: <i>emet</i> (faithfulness) emerges from the earth (<i>mitaretz titzmach</i>, springs up like a plant) while <i>tzedek</i> (righteousness) looks down from the sky (<i>min-shamayim nishqaph</i>). Heaven and earth participate in the restoration: the created order aligns with the covenant attributes. This mirrors the creation-restoration language of Isa 45:8 ('let the skies rain down righteousness; let the earth open and salvation and righteousness spring up together').</p>", "12": "<p><b>'Yes, the LORD will give what is good, and our land will yield its increase'</b> — the covenant blessing formula: YHWH gives the good (<i>hayyov</i>) and the land yields its produce (<i>artzenu titen yevulah</i>). Lev 26:4 and Deut 28:12 include agricultural abundance as the primary covenant blessing. The post-exilic community, farming on land depleted by the exile and return, receives the promise that YHWH's restoration includes material, agricultural flourishing.</p>", "13": "<p><b>'Righteousness will go before him and make his footsteps a way'</b> — <i>tzedek lefanav yehallech</i> (righteousness will walk before him) — righteousness personified as YHWH's advance-herald, the forerunner preparing the way. The closing verse envisions YHWH's approach as a royal procession: righteousness goes ahead, then YHWH walks, and his footsteps become the path that others follow. The herald-before-the-king imagery anticipates Isa 40:3 ('prepare the way of the LORD') and the NT's application of that text to John the Baptist.</p>"}}

if __name__ == '__main__':
    book = 'psalms'
    source = 'mkt-context'
    existing = load_comm(source, book)
    merge_comm(existing, NEW_DATA)
    save_comm(source, book, existing)
    for ch, vv in NEW_DATA.items():
        saved = existing.get(ch, {})
        missing = [v for v in vv if v not in saved]
        print(f'  ch {ch}: {len(vv)} entries, {len(missing)} missing after merge')
